{"actual_usd":0.126535,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":277,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"Maybe some pieces could be named that way, yes.\" *I hook one flour-dusted thumb into my apron pocket and glance toward the bakery window, where the light has gone warm on the sill.* \"Grief can do strange things to people, and people do survive things you'd swear would've finished them.\"\n\n\"But if you're asking me why a Christian insists on more than that...\" *I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through before I let it go.* \"Because at some point the natural explanation starts sounding more strained than the miracle. Not one hurting person seeing what he wanted to see, but a whole frightened little knot of people turning inside out and staking everything on 'he was dead, and now he isn't.' That's a big loaf to rise on grief alone.\"\n\n\"And the not-really-dead idea...\" *I give a small crooked look.* \"I think that's the weaker dough of the two. A man half-dead and staggering out of a tomb doesn't usually make people proclaim death beaten clean through. He makes them fetch water and linens.\"\n\n\"If Christ truly rose, then supernatural isn't an embarrassment tacked onto the story. It's the story.\" *I rest my palm on the warm stone by the window ledge a moment.* \"Which part feels more live to you—the visions theory, or the thought that he never quite died?\"","rolling_24h_usd":63.139005000000004,"run_id":"0b369845-520c-47ff-b717-af43a34d5f36"}
